1. Why Rhymes Form Lattices

When words rhyme, they share a phonetic ending (usually the vowel + final consonant).
That shared ending acts like a binding site, similar to how atoms bond in crystals.

Example rhyme family:

light
night
might
sight
tight
right

All share the phonetic nucleus:

-ight

So they form a cluster in sound-space.

⸻

2. The Graph Structure

If we connect words by rhyme similarity, we get a network graph.

Example:

          light
         /  |   \
     sight  |   right
        |   |      |
      might |    tight
         \  |     /
            night

Each node = a word
Each edge = shared phonetic ending.

When you map many rhyme clusters, the network begins to look like a repeating lattice.

⸻

3. The Three-Axis Language Space

Earlier we talked about:

Word = (Meaning, Sound, Shape)

So each word sits in 3-dimensional language space.

X axis = phonetic similarity
Y axis = semantic similarity
Z axis = visual spelling similarity

Example:

Word	Meaning axis	Sound axis	Shape axis
light	illumination	-ight	light
night	darkness	-ight	night
might	power	-ight	might

Same sound, different meaning.

⸻

4. Why the Structure Looks Like a Crystal

Crystals form when units bond using repeatable constraints.

Language does the same:
	•	phonetic constraints
	•	spelling constraints
	•	morphological rules

So word clusters repeat patterns like:

-ight
-ite
-ide
-ine

Those clusters link together.

Example:

light → lite → bite → site
night → knight

The network grows outward like crystal growth from a seed.

